metadata.name: The seed :: issue 1 #41
metadata.description:
*the seed* is an experimental project, meaning that we give ourselves permission to test the waters and see where the current takes us. *the seed* is also a zine, which suggests something both unpretentious and grassroots ‚Äî it's most definitely a labor of love!

The first issue is on the minimalist side, with a total of 19 pages nonetheless! We avoided big blocks of text and leaned into finding creative solutions to allow the artists to express themselves without having to produce new work. We also elected not to systematically showcase an artist's latest project as a way of jumping off the cultural treadmill which has conditioned us to focus almost exclusively on "what's new" and "what's next". As a result, *the seed*, which we envisage as a quarterly publication, will hopefully convey a certain quality of timelessness.

This issue is a collective invitation to catch our breath and celebrate the beauty that has been brought forth by a diverse group of amazing artists from all over the world: Lammetje, Liam Egan, Ciput, Elsif & Clint Fulkerson. Instead of asking the typical interview questions, we invited each artist to introduce themselves using a text based recording device which allows the reader to witness the workings of the artist's mind. The result feels both lighthearted and intimate.

The edition size is 128 and statistically one in five coverpages will be an animated collage created using the artwork of one of our five artists. No two coverpages are alike as the seed differs for each collage. This might be less apparent if the project is only examined through thumbnails. Please take the time to explore all of the interactive features of *the seed* on full screen.

*the seed* was made with C++ and OpenGL and converted to the web via Emscripten.

Thank you for reading this metadata and for coming on this journey with us!

I will be donating all proceeds from the minting of this project to plant trees.  Secondary royalties will be kept by me.  Thank you all ahead of time for your support!

metadata.name: ALL SEEING #35
metadata.description:
ALL SEEING explores the distribution of human eye colors by mapping color probabilities to each mint. Every artwork is different. Eye positioning, color, stroke and density is determined by a random seed hash. Color probability is loosely based on distribution across the human population, but weighted slightly to allow more color drops. For a lucky few, eyes become multicolored. If the hash gives it's blessing, there's a STAR MAN waiting in that rarest ~1% of mints that features a red background and a near fully-dialated pupil.

--- Features ---
Random eye color distributions of brown ~51% ,blue ~20%, hazel ~10%, amber ~5%, gray ~5%, green ~5%, heterochromia ~3%, and STAR MAN ~1%
Color density
White density

metadata.name: The Age of Automata #1
metadata.description:
This is an exploration of cellular automaton to find simplicity and beauty in mathematics.

First, a grid with random dimensions is created. A color palette is randomly selected from a large number of palettes, and a cellular automaton is formed based on one of the rules, and this operation may be repeated randomly to form a relatively more complex pattern. Finally, a number of geometries are combined with the automaton to make the mint harmonious and unique.

The idea was inspired by discoveries of Wolfram and Ciphrd‚Äôs artwork. 

Press ‚Äôs‚Äô on the live mode to save the artwork.

I recently launched my Twitter, so if you have any questions and would like to know about my next work or have a suggestion, you can contact me through this account:

https://twitter.com/_XSaha

Made with P5js.

metadata.name: Patched with Tartan #1
metadata.description:
Patched with Tartan is a generative patchwork made with p5.js. 
Evolving from my earlier work, "Patched", this new piece has 576 possible layout combinations, 17 new printed patterns on a choice of 7 new textile textures and two new woven fabrics with near infinite colour variation chosen from one of 13 palettes. 

This piece introduces a new tartan fabric which gives it its name. Due to the vagaries of generative art it is quite possible that a piece won't contain any tartan though so all holders of Patched with Tartan will receive free access to a brand new pure tartan token in a couple of weeks.

'2' to regenerate at 2000x2000
'3' to regenerate at 3000x3000
'r' to regenerate at window size

metadata.name: Fabric Remnants #38
metadata.description:
One of my sisters is a tailor and restorator. This piece is a homage to her. 
Shopping for fabric with her and seeing her atelier while she is working is a 
festival of color, shapes, patterns and a celebration of creativity.

This is my pragmatical take on her work. The fabric like texture and dashed lines
representing the yarn rearranged in a grid of leftovers.

The piece is a generated SVG, because of that it scales easily and is printable.

Use the arrow keys to toggle/tune some things & Space / click to regenerate a new
grid. The P key will toggle auto generation.
